{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Elene* (Chapter 1), after Judas unearths three crosses from Calvary and presents them to Elene, he cannot identify which is the True Cross. He sets the crosses in the city center and waits for a sign from God. At the ninth hour, a crowd brings a dead youth (\"a youth, spiritless\") on a bier. Judas lays the body down and raises the first two crosses over it—no effect. When he raises the third cross, the \"true victory-beacon,\" the youth immediately revives, rising \"with spirit endowed, together both body and soul,\" confirming it as the wood of the True Cross.[^1]**\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).",
